Figure 5.13 illustrates a non-inverting amplifier circuit. The signal source is denoted by $v_{g}$ in series with resistor $R_{g}$. To derive the output voltage as a function of the source voltage, we assume an ideal operational amplifier operating within its linear range. Consequently, we utilize Eqs. 5.2 and 5.3 as the foundation for our derivation. Given that the op amp's input current is zero, we can assert $v_{p}=v_{g}$ and, from Eq. 5.2, $v_{n}=v_{g}$ as well. Since the input current is zero ($i_{n}=i_{p}=0$), resistors $R_{f}$ and $R_{s}$ constitute an unloaded voltage divider across $v_{o}$. Therefore,

$$
\begin{equation*}
v_{n}=v_{g}=\frac{v_{o} R_{s}}{R_{s}+R_{f}} \tag{5.17}
\end{equation*}
$$

Solving Eq. 5.17 for $v_{o}$ yields the desired expression:

$$
\begin{equation*}
v_{o}=\frac{R_{s}+R_{f}}{R_{s}} v_{g} \tag{5.18}
\end{equation*}
$$

